| [[WP:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 2#Variety on Dragon Ball Z|1]] [[WP:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 20#Are Variety and The Hollywood Reporter reliable sources for film reviews?|2]] [[WP:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 29#Tucker Max and questions about 2 sources|3]] [[WP:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 160#imdb as a source for credits|4]] [[WP:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 207#Forbes article by credible contributor|5]]
| {{WP:RSPLAST|2016}}
| As an entertainment trade magazine, ''Variety'' is considered a reliable source in its field.
| {{WP:RSPUSES|variety.com}}

|- class="s-d" id="VDARE"
| [[VDARE]]
| {{WP:RSPSTATUS|d}}
| {{rsnl|254|RFC: VDARE|2018|rfc=y}}
| {{WP:RSPLAST|2019|stale=n}}
| VDARE was deprecated in the 2018 RfC. Editors agree that it is generally unusable as a source, although there may be rare exceptions such as in identifying its writers in an [[WP:ABOUTSELF|about-self fashion]]. Such limited instances will only be under careful and guided ("filtered") discretion.
| {{WP:RSPUSES|vdare.com}}

|- class="s-gu" id="Venezuelanalysis"
| [[Venezuelanalysis]] {{WP:RSPSHORTCUT|WP:VENEZUELANALYSIS}}
| {{WP:RSPSTATUS|gu}}
| {{rsnl|262|RfC: Venezuelanalysis|2019|rfc=y}} {{rsnl|420|RfC: Venezuelanalysis|2023|rfc=y}}
| {{WP:RSPLAST|2023|stale=n}}
| There is consensus that Venezuelanalysis is generally unreliable. Some editors consider Venezuelanalysis a [[Bolivarian propaganda]] outlet, and most editors question its accuracy and editorial oversight. Almost all editors describe the site as [[WP:BIASED|biased or opinionated]], so its claims should be [[WP:INTEXT|attributed]].
| {{WP:RSPUSES|venezuelanalysis.com}}

|- class="s-nc" id="VentureBeat"
| [[VentureBeat]] {{WP:RSPSHORTCUT|WP:VENTUREBEAT}}
| {{WP:RSPSTATUS|nc}}
| [[WP:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 105#VentureBeat|1]] [[WP:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 482#Reevaluating VentureBeat: Churnalism, notability and AI use|2]] [[WP:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 486#TechCrunch, VentureBeat, and Business Insider|3]]<br> [[Wikipedia talk:WikiProject Video games/Sources/Archive 12#Venturebeat/Gamesbeat|A]]
| {{WP:RSPLAST|2025}}
| There is no consensus on the reliability of VentureBeat. Some editors expressed concern over the site's publication of [[churnalism]] and AI-generated articles, and argued against using the site to establish [[WP:N|notability]]. WikiProject Video games has [[WP:VG/S#General gaming|classified VentureBeat]] as generally reliable for its coverage of video games.
| {{WP:RSPUSES|venturebeat.com}}

|- class="s-gr" id="The Verge"
| data-sort-value="Verge" | ''[[The Verge]]'' {{WP:RSPSHORTCUT|WP:THEVERGE}}
| {{WP:RSPSTATUS|gr}}
| {{rsnl|247|RfC about the reliability of The Verge as a source for use in articles relating to tech, science, culture, and cars|2018|rfc=y}}
| {{WP:RSPLAST|2024}}
| There is broad consensus that ''The Verge'' is a [[WP:RS|reliable source]] for use in articles relating to technology, science, and automobiles. Some editors question the quality of ''The Verge''{{'}}s instructional content on [[computer hardware]]. ''See also: {{pslink|Vox}}, {{pslink|Polygon (pre-May 2025)}}, {{pslink|New York}}''
| {{WP:RSPUSES|theverge.com}}

|- class="s-b" id="Veterans Today"
| ''[[Veterans Today]]''
| {{WP:RSPSTATUS|d|b=y}}
| {{rsnl|281|RfC: Deprecation of fake news / disinformation sites.|2019|rfc=y}}
| {{WP:RSPLAST|2019|stale=n}}
| Due to persistent abuse, ''Veterans Today'' is on the [[WP:SPB|Wikipedia spam blacklist]], and links must be [[Wikipedia talk:WHITELIST|whitelisted]] before they can be used. ''Veterans Today'' was deprecated in the 2019 RfC, which showed unanimous consensus that the site publishes [[fake news]] and [[antisemitism|antisemitic]] [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]]. The use of ''Veterans Today'' as a reference should be generally prohibited, especially when other sources exist that are more [[WP:RS|reliable]]. ''Veterans Today'' should not be used for determining [[WP:N|notability]], or used as a [[WP:SECONDARY|secondary source]] in articles.
| {{WP:RSPUSES|veteranstoday.com|vtforeignpolicy.com}}

|- class="s-gu" id="VGChartz"
| [[VGChartz]]
| {{WP:RSPSTATUS|gu}}
| {{rsnl|277|RfC: VGChartz|2019|rfc=y}}
| {{WP:RSPLAST|2019|stale=n}}
| In the 2019 RfC, editors unanimously agreed that VGChartz is generally unreliable. The site consists mainly of news articles that qualify as [[WP:UGC|user-generated content]]. In addition, editors heavily criticize VGChartz for poor accuracy standards in its video game sales data, and its methodology page consists of wholly unverified claims.<ref>{{cite web|last=Carless|first=Simon|date=June 23, 2008|df=mdy|url=https://www.gamedeveloper.com/game-platforms/analysis-what-vgchartz-does-and-doesn-t-do-for-the-game-biz|title=Analysis: What VGChartz Does (And Doesn't) Do For The Game Biz|work=[[Game Developer (website)|Game Developer]]|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref> If sources that are more reliable publish video game sales data for certain regions (usually [[Circana]], [[GfK Chart-Track]], and/or [[Media Create]]), it is strongly advised that editors cite those sources instead.
| {{WP:RSPUSES|vgchartz.com}}

|- class="s-nc" id="Vice Media"
| {{anchor|VICE|Vice}} [[Vice Media]] <small>(''[[Garage (magazine)|Garage]]'', ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', [[Vice News]], ''Motherboard'')</small> {{WP:RSPSHORTCUT|WP:VICE}}
| {{WP:RSPSTATUS|nc}}
| 17{{efn|See these discussions of Vice Media:
| {{WP:RSPLAST|2024}}
| There is no consensus on the reliability of [[Vice Media]] publications.
| {{WP:RSPUSES|vice.com|refinery29.com|vicetv.com}}

